You are ready to build Creaky Capreolus!

These instructions will guide you through the process of ordering the PCB for Creaky Capreolus, ordering the parts, preparing them, assembling your robot, and then programming it.

Ordering Your PCB

In order to build Creaky Capreolus, you'll need to have it's circuit board manufactured. There are many services online that will do this for you, but they each require a slightly different set of design files. The robot factory produces PCB design files that are compatible with 4PCB.com's student program, an reasonably priced and, in our experience, reliable option. Below are instructions for ordering from 4PCB.com as well as general instructions for ordering from other services.

Ordering Through 4PCB.com

To order through 4PCB, all you need is Creaky-Capreolus.cam.zip. It contains the "gerber" files that specify everything about your PCB. You can find this file inside the zip file you downloaded after the Robot Factory was finished building your robot.

Here are the steps for ordering:

  1. Visit http://www.4pcb.com/, and register for an account.
  2. Return 4pcb.com and login.
  3. Visit http://www.4pcb.com/pcb-prototype-2-4-layer-boards-specials.html, and select "Place Order" under "$33Each". A popup will appear, so be sure your pop-up blocker is turned off, if you have one.
  4. Login to your account
  5. Click "Choose file", and navigate to Creaky-Capreolus.cam.zip.
  6. Click "upload now"
  7. Enter values for "Part #" and "Rev #". These can be whatever you want, but "Creaky Capreolus" is a good choice.
  8. Enter the size of your PCB in inches: Width = 4.25; Height = 3.94.
  9. Make sure that "both side" is selected for "Soldermask" and "Silkscreen".
  10. Enter the quantity you want to order. If you are elligible for the student program, you can enter any number here. If you aren't, 4PCB says you have to order at least three boards (It's not clear if they enforce this).
  11. Select your shipping method. Shipping is pretty pricy, so consider using the slower, cheaper options.
  12. Select "No" for "ITAR".
  13. Enter your shipping and payment information
  14. If you are elligible for the student program, enter "Student" in the comments field.
  15. Click "Preview Order"
  16. If everything looks good, submit it and wait. It takes 5 business days to build the board.

Ordering Through Another Service

There are many other services besides 4PCB.com that will manufacture the PCB for Creaky Capreolus (e.g., Seeed Studio's Fusion PCB). Many of them are cheaper, but we have also found them to be less reliable. Your miliage may vary.

Robot Factory does not provide design files for these other services, but it does provide Eagle design files for Creaky Capreolus (Creaky-Capreolus.postroute.sch and Creaky-Capreolus.postroute.brd). You can use these (combined with a copy of Eagle's software) to generate the Gerbers that the service needs.

Doing this properly requires some expertise with Eagle, so if you haven't generated Gerbers in the past, you will need to find somen who can help you with the particular service you wish to use. Your local Makerspace is a good place to start.

Ordering Creaky Capreolus's Other Parts

The file contains the bill of materials for your robot. It contains a description of each part along with a distributor for it and the distributor's part number. Using that information, you can order everything you need for Creaky Capreolus.

Some of the parts are optional, so you can skip them. However, the resulting robot may be less sturdy and harder to disassemble, making it more difficult to reuse some parts for other projects.

Please note that some items (e.g., screws and LEDs) come in "packs" that contain more than one item. The number of these "packs" (or individual items if they are sold singly) you will need is listed in the "Packs Required + Optional" and "Packs Required" columns.

Many of the parts for Creaky Capreolus may also be available from other vendors and/or you may be able to find suitable substitutes.

Prepare the Parts

The first stage in assembling Creaky Capreolus is prepare the parts. This includes assembling and breakout board Creaky Capreolus uses as well as assembly motors and other complex parts of Creaky Capreolus that require extra work before attaching them to your PCB.

Soldering Headers

Some of Creaky Capreolus's components (like the micro controller) are breakout boards -- small circuit boards that you will attach to Creaky Capreolus.

Breakout boards provide male headers that allow you to attach them to Creaky Capreolus. If the headers are not already installed, you will need to solder them onto the breakout board.

If you haven't soldered before, don't worry: It is easy to learn, and assembling breakout boards is a good first project. Adafruit has an excellent tutorial on the subject.

The trick to attaching the headers is to make sure they are straight up and down. This ensure that your board looks good and that male and female headers will fit together nicely.

Here is our process for successful header soldering:

  1. Insert the header into the holes, and tape it place with masking tape.
  2. Apply solder to one pin to hold the header in place.
  3. Remove the tape, and check that the header is vertical.
  4. If it is not, use your soldering iron to remelt the solder on the first pin so you can adjust its position.
  5. Once you have it adjusted, apply solder to the other pins.

Assemble the PCB

Now, you will solder the components onto your PCB. If you are new to soldering, assembling Creaky Capreolus is good practice. The Robot Factory designed Creaky Capreolus to make it easy to solder.

If you need help, Adafruit has an excellent tutorial on the subject.

Reference Designators

Each part on a PCB has short name -- called a reference designator -- that identifies it. Reference designators are usually a letter or short sequence of letters that denote the type of component followed by a unique number. For instance, C1 would be a capacitor while R4 is a resistor. The letter "U" is a catchall for miscelleneous part types.

All the parts you will be soldering are "through hole" parts, which mean that they make an electrical connection to the board via "pins" that go through the holes in the PCB. By applying solder to the pin, while it's in the hole, you will form the connection.

Orienting Components

For most parts, it is important that you put the correct pins into the correct holes. To help you, the "primary" hole for each part looks different from the others, because its pad ring (the small patch of metal surrounding the hole) is a different shape -- square instead of round. If one pin on the part is longer than the other, it is the "primary" pin and should go into the "primary" hole.

Some parts have special rules about how to determine which pin should go in which hole. The instructions below descibe them as needed.

Soldering Components with Long Leads

Many through-hole electrical components come with long wire leads attached to them. We recommend the following steps for soldering one of these components to your PCB:

  1. Thread the leads through the holes from the front of the board (see the notes about orienting the component correctly above).
  2. While holding the component in place with your finger, and with the back of the board facing you, bend the leads out to the side so they hold the part in place.
  3. Apply solder on the back of the PCB where each lead comes through the board.
  4. Trim the leads at the top of the solder joint.

Installing Breakout Boards

In this stage you will install the breakout boards you assembled earlier. You have two options for attaching them to your PCB.

The first (and the one we provide instructions for below), uses female headers to allow you to temporarily attach the breakout board to your robot. This will let you reuse the breakout board in other projects (or on another robot).

In this case, you will solder the female headers to your board, and then plug the breakout board's male header into the female headers.

The second option is to solder the breakout board directly to your PCB. In this case, the breakout board will be more securely attach, and Creaky Capreolus will look a little better. However, it is very difficult to remove the breakout board in this case (unless you have something like this).

Soldering Wires

A few components require you to solder wires into holes on the PCB. Here are detailed instructions:

  1. Begin by stripping 1cm or so of insulation off the wire using wire strippers.
  2. If the wire is stranded (i.e., it's made up of many smaller wires), twist the exposed wires so they form a tight bundle.
  3. Insert the tip of the wire through hole in the PCB, and apply solder from the opposite side of the board.
  4. Trim off the excess wire.

  2. Adafruit Pro Trinket - 5V 16MHz

  3. Battery

    Use the steps below to assemble this part.
    1. Check that the battery fits, but don't install it until the rest of the robot is assembled.

Programming

Creaky Capreolus is based on an Arduino microcontroller (in particular, the Adafruit Pro Trinket), and you can program it using your computer. Follow the directions below to get started.

Installing Arduino

Visit the Arduino Downloads page to download the latest version of the Arduino integrated development environment (IDE). Follow the instruction on the site for installing it.

Getting Started With the Pro Trinket and Connecting to

If you haven't used an Arduino before, it'll be easier if you familiarize yourself with it first before programming Creaky Capreolus. Adafruit has an excellent tutorial on getting started with the Pro Trinket. You can remove your Pro Trinket from Creaky Capreolus and go through the tutorial.

One note: There are two ways to program a Pro Trinket (and, therefore, Creaky Capreolus): Using USB directly or using an FTDI adapter. We recommend using the FTDI adapter. To do so, follow the instructions here.

Installing the Gadgetron Libraries

The Gadgetron libraries contains all the Arduino libraries needed to interact with the breakout boards and parts available in the Robot Factory software.

To install the Gadgetron Libraries first open your Arduino IDE and navigate to Sketch -> Include Library -> Manage Libraries... . After that a popup window will open with a list of Arduino libraries you can install. Search there for Gadgetron Libraries and install this library.

Now the Gadgetron Libraries should be installed and ready to use.

If you have problems finding the library you can manually install the library by following the next steps.

First download the following zip file ( gadgetron-software-libraries-1.0.0.zip). After downloading the zip file open your Arduino IDE and go to Sketch -> Include Library -> Add .ZIP Library . Finally select the zip file you just downloaded to install the Gadgetron Libraries.

Running Creaky Capreolus's Sample Code

The zip file tha contains these instructions also contains a file called Creaky-Capreolus.ino. It contains a simple program that will test all the parts of Creaky Capreolus. Open it from inside the Arduino IDE.

You should be able to compile and download the program to Creaky Capreolus. Once it's running, it should briefly activate each of the components on Creaky Capreolus (e.g., the wheels will turn briefly, the LEDs will flash).

If you assembled Creaky Capreolus correctly, everything should work fine.

If it doesn't here are some things to check for:

  • Make sure your battery is fresh.
  • Make sure all your breakout boards are installed properly (e.g., that Pro Trinket is not installed backward).

Additional Examples and Documentation

Once you've confirmed that all the parts of Creaky Capreolus work as expected, you can start programming it to do what you want!

You can find additional example code for each of the component by selecting "File->Examples" and choosing the component you would like to learn more about.

Debugging and Common Problems

If the battery is powering a microcontroller and the microcontroller resets frequently, that is a good sign that the battery is dying and needs to be replaced.
